"{\n  \"text\": \"You can't use tap water when you're fermenting. This is kind of an issue because tap water has chlorine or chloramines in it, which are antibacterial agents. When you're fermenting, you're cultivating bacteria on the on the vegetables that you're fermenting in the fruits or what have you. And this is real important because a lot of people come to me and say, I tried to ferment something, it just didn't work out. Almost 100% of the time it's the water. If you're using some sort of antibacter or if the water you're using has some sort of antibacterial agent in it, you'll find that you have poor results if not just complete failure. So make sure that the water you're using is a good quality water. A purified water tends to not be quite as clean as a lot of people think. Adding chlorine and then trying to take it out later it depends on a lot on the quality of the filters and how new they are and things of this nature. So you can't always trust the purified water and you'll find that out when you're fermenting. I certainly did. Anyway, thanks y'all.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" You can't use tap water when you're fermenting.\",\n      \"start\": 0.56,\n      \"end\": 2.88,\n      \"duration\": 2.32,\n      \"confidence\": 0.996,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" You\",\n          \"start\": 0.56,\n          \"end\": 0.8,\n          \"duration\": 0.24,\n          \"confidence\": 0.996\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" can\",\n          \"start\": 0.8,\n          \"end\": 0.88,\n          \"duration\": 0.08,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"'\",\n          \"start\": 0.88,\n          \"end\": 1.04,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"t\",\n          \"start\": 1.04,\n          \"end\": 1.12,\n          \"duration\": 0.08,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n         